	<tr>
		
			<td colspan="2" bgcolor="#DEDACB" background="http://www.everlore.com/gimages/tb_beige.gif">
		
				<font face="verdana" size="2" color="black">
				I went on a dragon raid last night, and a friend of mine won the scale. I wanted to do a little research for him. I am a master Jeweler (Skill 200), and I was trying to describe to him how hard it is to make the Black Sapphire Necklace and the Diamond ring. First, platinum is never trivial. Second, jewelry items do become trivial on a fairly regulated scale (Thanks Verant). The following examples show you the rough difficulty to make the items needed.<BR>
<BR>
Silver Peridot - Trivial @ 46<BR>
Electrum Peridot - Trivial @ 115 (Diff 69)<BR>
Gold Peridot - Trivial @ 185 (Diff 70)<BR>
Platinum Peridot - Est. Trivial @ 255 (Added 70)<BR>
<BR>
The final trivial a Jeweler can make is the Gold Star Ruby.<BR>
<BR>
Gold Star Ruby - Trivial at 199<BR>
Platinum Star Ruby - Est. Trival @ 269 (Added 70)<BR>
<BR>
Finally on the ascending scale of Jeweling, the Black Sapphire and Diamond are the fifth and sixth gems above Star Ruby.<BR>
<BR>
Platinum Black Sapphire - Est. Trivial @ 282<BR>
Platinum Diamond - Est. Trivial @ 285<BR>
<BR>
Now that you have all these numbers, I will put them into perspective.<BR>
<BR>
It is about the same as Researching Ice Comet with a 100 in Research or making a 10 slot pack with a 5 in tailoring. It can be done. Rough estimate on success is one in eight to ten tries. This number can be decreased through finding a Jeweler with a high Wisdom.<BR>
<BR>
Hope this helps.<BR>
<BR>
Cidric D'Borgoe<BR>
Enchanter/Master Jeweler<BR>
Crystalline Knights<BR>
Lanys Server
				</font>
			</td>

	</tr>
	
